LISTERIOSIS - FRANCE: BACKGROUND
********************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
See Also
Listeriosis - France 20000219195424
Date: Sun, 20 Feb 2000 06:29:31 +0200
From: Stephen Berger <mberger@post.tau.ac.il>

Listeriosis is a very hot topic in France. The following background data were
extracted from the GIDEON software program. See <http://www.cynifo.com>
During 1995 to 1996, highest disease rates were reported from Limousin,
Rhone-Alpes and Basse-Normandie. In 1998, highest incidence was reported
from Auvergne, Basse-Normandie and Pays de Loire.
CASES REPORTED NATIONWIDE - BY YEAR
Year Perinatal Non-Perinatal Meningitis
1987 185 181 188
1988 171 226 171
1989 192 217 218
1990 111 194 130
1991 170 217 173
1992 153 584 254
1993 144 345 101
1994 73 263 76
1995 61 240 56
1996 59 161 42
1997 53 175 45
1998 47 183
The rate of _Listeria_ meningitis (and invasive infection) was 0.30/100 000
(0.85/100 000) in 1991; 0.09/100 000 (0.41/100 000) in 1997.
Outbreaks of Listeriosis:
278 of the cases reported in 1992 were associated with outbreaks; 28 in
1993; 37 in 1995.
- An outbreak in 1976 (Anjou) of 162 cases (134 perinatal) was not
ascribed to a specific source.
- An outbreak in 1992 of 279 cases (63 deaths and 22 associated abortions)
was traced to pork tongue.
- An outbreak in 1993 of 39 cases (31 perinatal) was ascribed to rillettes
(potted mince).
- An outbreak in 1995 of 37 cases (18 perinatal) was ascribed to brie cheese.
- An outbreak in 1996 of 10 cases was not ascribed to a specific source.
- An outbreak in 1999 of 6 cases (2 fatal) was ascribed to rillettes.
--
